Thank you.

00:01:01.000 --> 00:01:02.041
JOSHUA HAMMER: Thank you.

00:01:02.041 --> 00:01:04.644
[APPLAUSE]

00:01:04.644 --> 00:01:06.141
Thanks a lot.

00:01:06.141 --> 00:01:08.475
What I thought I
would do, and I've

00:01:08.475 --> 00:01:11.926
honed this after a couple
of book talks in New York,

00:01:11.926 --> 00:01:16.190
is give you a little rundown
of the arc of this story

00:01:16.190 --> 00:01:17.660
and how I happened
to come to it.

00:01:17.660 --> 00:01:20.710
And then I will accompany
that with some pictures

00:01:20.710 --> 00:01:26.040
so you can get a sense of what
this very unusual, desolate,

00:01:26.040 --> 00:01:27.789
but somehow beautiful
part of the world

00:01:27.789 --> 00:01:29.830
is all-- what it looks
like, what it's all about.

00:01:29.830 --> 00:01:32.245
And then I would read
a couple passages

00:01:32.245 --> 00:01:33.870
and then ask if you
have any questions.

00:01:33.870 --> 00:01:36.960
So Timbuktu-- how did
I come upon this place?

00:01:36.960 --> 00:01:42.380
I was "Newsweek's" Africa bureau
chief in the '90s and kind of

00:01:42.380 --> 00:01:46.060
had carte blanche to travel
all across sub-Saharan Africa,

00:01:46.060 --> 00:01:49.560
basically doing whatever
I wanted to do in the days

00:01:49.560 --> 00:01:51.790
when that kind of
journalism was still--

00:01:51.790 --> 00:01:55.690
when news weeklies and
other media organizations

00:01:55.690 --> 00:01:58.490
had deep pockets and could
let their correspondents just

00:01:58.490 --> 00:02:00.710
wander the world.

00:02:00.710 --> 00:02:04.190
So a couple of colleagues and
I in 1995 went to Timbuktu.

00:02:04.190 --> 00:02:06.630
We chartered a small plane
in Bamako, the capital,

00:02:06.630 --> 00:02:08.660
and flew up there for two hours.

00:02:08.660 --> 00:02:12.029
Because it was expensive to
charter your own airplane.

00:02:12.029 --> 00:02:13.320
And they weren't that generous.

00:02:13.320 --> 00:02:15.550
So we flew in, and we
wandered the streets

00:02:15.550 --> 00:02:19.750
of this ancient
town, desolate town.

00:02:19.750 --> 00:02:21.730
There was a war going on.

00:02:21.730 --> 00:02:24.500
The nomadic people known
as Tuaregs were in revolt.

00:02:24.500 --> 00:02:27.340
And so there was basically--
there were no tourists.

00:02:27.340 --> 00:02:31.692
There was basically no
transportation in or out.

00:02:31.692 --> 00:02:33.400
We managed to get in
there, and wandered,

00:02:33.400 --> 00:02:37.930
and saw the mud huts
where the explorers

00:02:37.930 --> 00:02:40.360
from the early 19th
century had stayed

00:02:40.360 --> 00:02:43.390
when they managed to get
into Timbuktu back then

00:02:43.390 --> 00:02:46.150
and where one of them had
been executed after it

00:02:46.150 --> 00:02:49.090
was found he was not a Muslim.

00:02:49.090 --> 00:02:52.470
So it was a desolate,
kind of depressing place.

00:02:52.470 --> 00:02:55.290
But also obviously had
this incredibly rich,

00:02:55.290 --> 00:02:56.890
legendary history behind it.

00:02:56.890 --> 00:02:59.180
And I was definitely hooked
right then and there.

00:02:59.180 --> 00:03:02.130
Then 10 years later,
I left "Newsweek"

00:03:02.130 --> 00:03:04.340
and went freelance and
began looking around

00:03:04.340 --> 00:03:08.790
for ideas, always on the search
for ideas to keep working.

00:03:08.790 --> 00:03:12.730
Came across a small item
about these manuscripts

00:03:12.730 --> 00:03:16.750
from the Middle Ages that
had been rediscovered

00:03:16.750 --> 00:03:18.960
in and around Timbuktu.

00:03:18.960 --> 00:03:23.050
And the article went on to say
that there was an effort led

00:03:23.050 --> 00:03:27.300
by a couple of librarians
to collect them--

00:03:27.300 --> 00:03:29.890
I don't think the
digitization was yet part

00:03:29.890 --> 00:03:31.160
of the process at that point.

00:03:31.160 --> 00:03:33.600
But it was simply collecting
them and restoring them,

00:03:33.600 --> 00:03:36.320
building libraries and trying
to show them to the world.

00:03:36.320 --> 00:03:38.150
It definitely
caught my attention

00:03:38.150 --> 00:03:40.060
given my previous
trip to Timbuktu

00:03:40.060 --> 00:03:44.220
and my interest in literature,
and the preservation

00:03:44.220 --> 00:03:48.900
of manuscripts, and
cultural patrimony.

00:03:48.900 --> 00:03:51.740
Called an editor at
"Smithsonian Magazine,"

00:03:51.740 --> 00:03:53.467
which does that kind
of thing-- exactly

00:03:53.467 --> 00:03:54.550
what would appeal to them.

00:03:54.550 --> 00:03:58.650
And within a week, I was on
another plane up to Timbuktu.

00:03:58.650 --> 00:03:59.790
This is what I confronted.

00:03:59.790 --> 00:04:01.460
This is the Sankore
mosque, which

00:04:01.460 --> 00:04:03.340
was built in the 14th century.

00:04:03.340 --> 00:04:05.510
The typical architecture
of that period,

00:04:05.510 --> 00:04:10.850
when it was really a
unique architecture that's

00:04:10.850 --> 00:04:13.190
sort of influenced by
the Egyptian pyramids

00:04:13.190 --> 00:04:18.959
but given its own kind
of North African motif.

00:04:18.959 --> 00:04:22.952
Streets look like that-- mix
of mud brick and limestone.

00:04:22.952 --> 00:04:25.300
And better houses were made
of these limestone bricks,

00:04:25.300 --> 00:04:26.200
as you see.

00:04:26.200 --> 00:04:29.460
Mud alleys-- not the
kind of grand city

00:04:29.460 --> 00:04:33.900
paved with gold that
had lured the Europeans

00:04:33.900 --> 00:04:36.080
in the early 19th century.

00:04:36.080 --> 00:04:39.410
Another shot of the oldest
neighborhood of Timbuktu--

00:04:39.410 --> 00:04:42.840
Sankore, it's called.

00:04:42.840 --> 00:04:47.440
During that trip, I met this
gentleman, Abdul Kader Haidara.

00:04:47.440 --> 00:04:49.920
He was the most
charismatic figure

00:04:49.920 --> 00:04:52.750
in Timbuktu in this
manuscript effort.

00:04:52.750 --> 00:04:55.440
What he had done
single handedly,

00:04:55.440 --> 00:04:59.760
practically, was to rediscover
this incredible tradition

00:04:59.760 --> 00:05:03.120
of manuscript writing that
had flourished in Timbuktu

00:05:03.120 --> 00:05:04.650
in the 15th and 16th centuries.

00:05:04.650 --> 00:05:08.580
This desolate place
had 500 years ago

00:05:08.580 --> 00:05:11.380
been at the center
of the commerce

00:05:11.380 --> 00:05:16.860
and cultural life of that
period in Northern Africa.

00:05:16.860 --> 00:05:21.830
It was a place where the
river met the desert, where

00:05:21.830 --> 00:05:23.680
the highest bend
of the Niger River,

00:05:23.680 --> 00:05:26.830
the third longest river
in Africa, met the Sahara.

00:05:26.830 --> 00:05:31.150
So you had this constant
stream of transport,

00:05:31.150 --> 00:05:33.860
of commercial transport,
coming from across the Sahara

00:05:33.860 --> 00:05:36.860
Desert from as far away as
Europe, bringing textiles,

00:05:36.860 --> 00:05:40.690
clothing, whatever they
could-- whatever came out

00:05:40.690 --> 00:05:41.940
of that part of the world.

00:05:41.940 --> 00:05:45.050
Then river traffic coming
up from sub-Saharan Africa

00:05:45.050 --> 00:05:49.485
bringing everything from
kola nuts, to slaves-- it

00:05:49.485 --> 00:05:52.920
was a big slave
trading port-- to gold.

00:05:52.920 --> 00:05:57.930
So over the centuries,
this outpost

00:05:57.930 --> 00:06:01.250
at the very edge of the Sahara
became an incredibly wealthy

00:06:01.250 --> 00:06:02.370
place.

00:06:02.370 --> 00:06:07.160
At the same time, under a
couple of enlightened rulers,

00:06:07.160 --> 00:06:09.390
it became a center
of intellectuality,

00:06:09.390 --> 00:06:11.260
of scholasticism.

00:06:11.260 --> 00:06:14.810
Universities were founded in
the 15th and 16th centuries.

00:06:14.810 --> 00:06:17.580
Thousands of students
came to Timbuktu

00:06:17.580 --> 00:06:19.570
from all across the Arab world.

00:06:19.570 --> 00:06:24.433
An industry creating manuscripts
it was founded around 1400,

00:06:24.433 --> 00:06:25.970
or 1500, or so.

00:06:25.970 --> 00:06:30.520
In between that period, you had
hundreds of scribes turning out

00:06:30.520 --> 00:06:32.940
using beautiful calligraphy,
and beautiful colors,

00:06:32.940 --> 00:06:35.460
and beautiful
pattern and designs,

00:06:35.460 --> 00:06:40.450
works that range from Korans,
the Hadith, the sayings

00:06:40.450 --> 00:06:43.520
of the prophet, to
secular works including

00:06:43.520 --> 00:06:46.220
works of astronomy,
works of medicine,

00:06:46.220 --> 00:06:49.510
poetry, guides to orgasm.

00:06:49.510 --> 00:06:52.290
You name it, everything
could be found

00:06:52.290 --> 00:06:55.020
in Timbuktu-- how-to books,
I should say-- how-to books

00:06:55.020 --> 00:06:56.170
about sex.

00:06:56.170 --> 00:06:59.090
That was a real popular
seller in about 1550.

00:06:59.090 --> 00:07:04.790
So this incredible trade
flourished for 100 years

00:07:04.790 --> 00:07:07.930
or so during this
golden era of Timbuktu.

00:07:07.930 --> 00:07:10.860
It showed a kind
of Islam that was

00:07:10.860 --> 00:07:16.240
tolerant, open, cross-cultural,
multicultural, open to ideas,

00:07:16.240 --> 00:07:21.380
able to synthesize both religion
and science in a unique way.

00:07:21.380 --> 00:07:23.820
It lasted, as I said,
for about a century.

00:07:23.820 --> 00:07:27.500
And then in the late
16th century, about 1591,

00:07:27.500 --> 00:07:31.900
Moroccan invaders swept across
the Sahara, conquered Timbuktu,

00:07:31.900 --> 00:07:35.350
took many of these scholars
and scribes into captivity.

00:07:35.350 --> 00:07:37.760
A lot of them were
resistant-- became

00:07:37.760 --> 00:07:40.290
members of the resistance
against the colonial occupiers.

00:07:40.290 --> 00:07:42.400
So they were either
killed or enslaved

00:07:42.400 --> 00:07:44.590
and dragged across the
desert back to Morocco

00:07:44.590 --> 00:07:47.280
where they spent either the
rest of their lives or years

00:07:47.280 --> 00:07:48.250
in captivity.

00:07:48.250 --> 00:07:51.840
That pretty much
ended Timbuktu's reign

00:07:51.840 --> 00:07:56.440
as the center or scholasticism
of this part of the world.

00:07:56.440 --> 00:07:58.230
At the same time,
cultural-- sorry,

00:07:58.230 --> 00:08:00.010
trade routes were changing.

00:08:00.010 --> 00:08:03.440
This whole desert trade was
no longer that important.

00:08:03.440 --> 00:08:05.900
And as time went
on, Timbuktu kind of

00:08:05.900 --> 00:08:09.740
faded into insignificance of
became this, as I have said,

00:08:09.740 --> 00:08:13.040
this desolate outpost that
the Europeans stumbled

00:08:13.040 --> 00:08:14.280
into in the 19th century.

00:08:14.280 --> 00:08:15.880
And they got there,
as I said, having

00:08:15.880 --> 00:08:17.860
heard these legends
about this city of gold

00:08:17.860 --> 00:08:20.730
and stumbled upon this place
that was pretty much-- well,

00:08:20.730 --> 00:08:23.750
you saw the pictures
before-- just a dusty,

00:08:23.750 --> 00:08:27.790
poor, monochromatic,
pretty insignificant pace.

00:08:27.790 --> 00:08:30.330
So there was tremendous joy
at having reached Timbuktu,

00:08:30.330 --> 00:08:32.490
but at the same time
great disappointment.

00:08:32.490 --> 00:08:38.919
Abdel Kader Haidara had a unique
story, a pretty extraordinary

00:08:38.919 --> 00:08:39.480
story.

00:08:39.480 --> 00:08:45.600
This gentleman was the son
of a scholar in Timbuktu,

00:08:45.600 --> 00:08:49.830
became interested in Timbuktu's
lost literary tradition

00:08:49.830 --> 00:08:51.700
as a young man, as a teenager.

00:08:51.700 --> 00:08:55.900
And I should also point
out that not only did

00:08:55.900 --> 00:08:58.970
Timbuktu become a desolate
place, poverty stricken place,

00:08:58.970 --> 00:09:02.220
but the whole tradition
of literature,

00:09:02.220 --> 00:09:05.870
of learning was lost to the
point where enlightenment

00:09:05.870 --> 00:09:10.460
philosophers in Europe-- Hegel,
Locke, Kant-- wrote articles,

00:09:10.460 --> 00:09:13.100
wrote books saying that the
Africans have given us nothing.

00:09:13.100 --> 00:09:16.330
The Africans have given
us-- have no civilization,

00:09:16.330 --> 00:09:20.710
have no written traditions,
were illiterate savages.

00:09:20.710 --> 00:09:22.370
The Enlightenment
philosophers' views

00:09:22.370 --> 00:09:25.640
were instrumental in
justifying the slave trade.

00:09:25.640 --> 00:09:27.300
Because they
propagated this idea

00:09:27.300 --> 00:09:29.675
that Africans were sub-humans.

00:09:29.675 --> 00:09:31.540
And therefore, taking
them into captivity

00:09:31.540 --> 00:09:32.900
was perfectly acceptable.

00:09:32.900 --> 00:09:34.330
It should be pointed
out of course

00:09:34.330 --> 00:09:37.880
that the people in Timbuktu
back then also participated

00:09:37.880 --> 00:09:38.710
in the slave trade.

00:09:38.710 --> 00:09:42.690
So this wasn't the specific
to the European point of view.

00:09:42.690 --> 00:09:45.470
But anyway, Abdel
Kader was determined

00:09:45.470 --> 00:09:47.510
to rescue this lost tradition.

00:09:47.510 --> 00:09:51.760
So he was hired in 1984 by
the Ahmed Baba Center, which

00:09:51.760 --> 00:09:56.710
was a government owned library
funded by the royal-- governed

00:09:56.710 --> 00:10:00.955
by the royal families of
Kuwait and Saudi Arabia.

00:10:00.955 --> 00:10:03.330
He was hired to go out-- he
was a bit reluctant at first.

00:10:03.330 --> 00:10:05.180
He said to me, I want
to go into businesses.

00:10:05.180 --> 00:10:07.670
His father had actually
become a fairly wealthy man

00:10:07.670 --> 00:10:10.210
trading livestock and grain
as well as maintaining

00:10:10.210 --> 00:10:11.780
his own private library.

00:10:11.780 --> 00:10:14.520
Abdel Kader kind of leaned
towards the money-making side

00:10:14.520 --> 00:10:18.550
of his father's career
but was persuaded

00:10:18.550 --> 00:10:21.570
by the chief
librarian, who appealed

00:10:21.570 --> 00:10:25.510
to his sense of national
duty and his love of books

00:10:25.510 --> 00:10:27.060
to go out hit the road.

00:10:27.060 --> 00:10:28.780
And this guy really
did hit the road.

00:10:28.780 --> 00:10:31.270
He went out, spent
the next 12 years

00:10:31.270 --> 00:10:36.520
of his life traveling by
camel, on foot, by riverboat

00:10:36.520 --> 00:10:40.140
through desert along
the Niger River.

00:10:40.140 --> 00:10:41.859
Let's just-- I
actually forgot to just

00:10:41.859 --> 00:10:43.900
give you a little sense
of these books look like.

00:10:43.900 --> 00:10:45.399
So let's quickly
flip through these.

00:10:45.399 --> 00:10:49.100
And then I'll continue Abdel
Kader's story very briefly.

00:10:49.100 --> 00:10:52.310
So this actually appears as
the end-piece in my book,

00:10:52.310 --> 00:10:55.080
because I think it's one of
the most beautiful pieces.

00:10:55.080 --> 00:10:57.350
I believe this is a Koran
from the 16th century.

00:10:57.350 --> 00:11:04.050
And you can see gold leaf, earth
colors derived from minerals,

00:11:04.050 --> 00:11:06.250
from insects, from plants.

00:11:06.250 --> 00:11:10.890
Because of the prohibitions in
Islam against representations

00:11:10.890 --> 00:11:13.840
of the human form, they
resorted to, instead,

00:11:13.840 --> 00:11:15.560
these incredibly
intricate patterns

00:11:15.560 --> 00:11:17.590
that were meant to
kind of demonstrate

00:11:17.590 --> 00:11:23.920
the universality, the harmony
of existence under God.

00:11:23.920 --> 00:11:29.310
And you have-- this is a book,
I believe, a diagram possibly

00:11:29.310 --> 00:11:30.250
of poetry.

00:11:30.250 --> 00:11:31.875
One of the things
about the manuscripts

00:11:31.875 --> 00:11:34.333
is that very few of them have
been translated into English.

00:11:34.333 --> 00:11:36.130
So unless you could
read classical Arabic,

00:11:36.130 --> 00:11:37.550
you're kind of lost.

00:11:37.550 --> 00:11:39.370
But you know, you
can still appreciate

00:11:39.370 --> 00:11:45.880
the beauty these books, some
really extraordinary works.

00:11:45.880 --> 00:11:48.400
I mean, and we're talking
thousands and thousands

00:11:48.400 --> 00:11:48.900
of these.

00:11:48.900 --> 00:11:51.233
So back to Abdel Kader-- this
is the kind of landscape--

00:11:51.233 --> 00:11:53.830
this is the road to
Timbuktu if you could even

00:11:53.830 --> 00:11:55.180
imagine there's a road there.

00:11:55.180 --> 00:11:56.721
It's basically just
a sand track that

00:11:56.721 --> 00:12:00.750
runs for 100 miles to the
very edge of the Sahara

00:12:00.750 --> 00:12:02.400
from southern Mali.

00:12:02.400 --> 00:12:06.980
Well, he was traveling for years
across this kind of landscape

00:12:06.980 --> 00:12:08.895
getting clues about books.

00:12:08.895 --> 00:12:15.610
You know, hey, I hear there's
a Qadi, a traditional judge,

00:12:15.610 --> 00:12:18.240
in a village on the Niger
River 100 miles from Timbuktu

00:12:18.240 --> 00:12:21.750
who has a box in a hidden
storage room which has

00:12:21.750 --> 00:12:23.000
a Koran from the 12th century.

00:12:23.000 --> 00:12:24.625
He would get these
clues, and then he'd

00:12:24.625 --> 00:12:27.350
head off on these incredible
journeys that sometimes lasted

00:12:27.350 --> 00:12:31.870
a month carrying lots
of cash, bargaining,

00:12:31.870 --> 00:12:36.990
developed a keen sense the
worth of these volumes.

00:12:36.990 --> 00:12:41.180
Again, more of kind of landscape
of this part of the world--

00:12:41.180 --> 00:12:44.400
this is called La Dune
Rose, the pink dune,

00:12:44.400 --> 00:12:47.770
along the Niger River,
a 90-foot sand dune

00:12:47.770 --> 00:12:49.160
towering over the stream.

00:12:49.160 --> 00:12:52.120
Traveling by riverboat-- a
little bit better than this.

00:12:52.120 --> 00:12:55.080
I mean, they had motors
at least-- along the Niger

00:12:55.080 --> 00:12:59.190
for days and weeks--
and managed to amass

00:12:59.190 --> 00:13:03.030
an incredible collection--
by the end, personally

00:13:03.030 --> 00:13:06.590
probably about 100,000 works
for the Ahmed Baba Center.

00:13:06.590 --> 00:13:09.500
After that, he developed
his own library

00:13:09.500 --> 00:13:13.810
based on the books that had been
in his family for generations.

00:13:13.810 --> 00:13:17.430
By this point-- an
