00:21:28.550 --> 00:21:32.500
But they basically
were and continue

00:21:32.500 --> 00:21:38.410
to be the only security
that this desolate city has

00:21:38.410 --> 00:21:40.470
protecting it.

00:21:40.470 --> 00:21:42.280
That essentially is
the arc of the story.

00:21:42.280 --> 00:21:43.770
Now I just thought I'd
give you a little bit

00:21:43.770 --> 00:21:44.710
of a sense of the book.

00:21:44.710 --> 00:21:46.100
I'm going to read a
couple-- I've been

00:21:46.100 --> 00:21:47.224
going for about 33 minutes.

00:21:47.224 --> 00:21:52.240
So let me read two passages
from this book that

00:21:52.240 --> 00:21:56.460
will kind of give you
a taste of Abdel Kader.

00:21:56.460 --> 00:22:02.630
And the first one is, which I've
found has had a good response,

00:22:02.630 --> 00:22:08.720
gives us a sense of
his bargaining efforts.

00:22:08.720 --> 00:22:12.360
So Abdel Kader would
go out into the bush.

00:22:12.360 --> 00:22:17.380
And he would bargain
with the locals.

00:22:17.380 --> 00:22:18.930
As I said, he would
get these clues

00:22:18.930 --> 00:22:21.080
about the existence
of these manuscripts

00:22:21.080 --> 00:22:22.480
and would track them down.

00:22:22.480 --> 00:22:25.431
And then he'd have to enter
into these negotiations.

00:22:25.431 --> 00:22:26.680
It was a very difficult thing.

00:22:26.680 --> 00:22:28.929
The first thing, people--
and I should point this out.

00:22:28.929 --> 00:22:31.880
I don't think I mentioned in my
talk that people were fearful.

00:22:31.880 --> 00:22:34.770
These manuscripts had,
over the centuries,

00:22:34.770 --> 00:22:37.320
been disbursed through families.

00:22:37.320 --> 00:22:41.040
There had been a succession
of attacks on Timbuktu

00:22:41.040 --> 00:22:43.130
by 19th century jihadists.

00:22:43.130 --> 00:22:47.175
The French colonizers had
come in and captured the area

00:22:47.175 --> 00:22:49.480
and held it for 70, 80 years.

00:22:49.480 --> 00:22:53.740
Manuscripts were highly
sought after by the French.

00:22:53.740 --> 00:22:57.560
The French had grabbed and
stolen many beautiful works,

00:22:57.560 --> 00:23:00.630
whisked them off to libraries
in Paris and then elsewhere

00:23:00.630 --> 00:23:01.570
in France.

00:23:01.570 --> 00:23:04.045
So by the time Abdel
Kader came around--

00:23:04.045 --> 00:23:08.630
and I neglected to tell you
this part of the story, what he

00:23:08.630 --> 00:23:10.800
was doing in the first place.

00:23:10.800 --> 00:23:13.060
They had been dispersed
throughout the desert.

00:23:13.060 --> 00:23:15.650
They had left their
original home in Timbuktu.

00:23:15.650 --> 00:23:19.100
As I said, families
would pass them down

00:23:19.100 --> 00:23:21.310
to generations of
sons and daughters.

00:23:21.310 --> 00:23:23.310
So they would be dispersed
through the families.

00:23:23.310 --> 00:23:26.720
And then because of this
fear of losing them,

00:23:26.720 --> 00:23:30.300
they would be further dispersed
and buried in the sand,

00:23:30.300 --> 00:23:33.510
and hidden in storage
rooms in villages and towns

00:23:33.510 --> 00:23:37.890
all through the Niger, all
through upper Northern Mali.

00:23:37.890 --> 00:23:40.420
So by the time Abdel
Kader came and had

00:23:40.420 --> 00:23:42.781
to try to find these works,
there was a lot of fear

00:23:42.781 --> 00:23:43.280
out there.

00:23:43.280 --> 00:23:46.810
People were extremely
reluctant to surrender

00:23:46.810 --> 00:23:49.300
what they viewed as
their family heirlooms

00:23:49.300 --> 00:23:50.520
and valuable collection.

00:23:50.520 --> 00:23:53.170
So he had a great
amount of difficulty

00:23:53.170 --> 00:23:56.340
at first getting a
hold of these things.

00:23:56.340 --> 00:23:58.160
But his techniques improved.

00:23:58.160 --> 00:24:00.510
And he was able to
get more and more--

00:24:00.510 --> 00:24:03.970
he was able to figure out
ways of encouraging people

00:24:03.970 --> 00:24:05.560
and became more and
more successful.

00:24:05.560 --> 00:24:09.350
So this is a typical scene
of Abdel Kader at work.

00:24:09.350 --> 00:24:12.860
"People also sensed that
Haidara was playing fair.

00:24:12.860 --> 00:24:15.810
After nearly being run
out of Gorma Rharous,

00:24:15.810 --> 00:24:18.240
the first town he
visited, Haidara

00:24:18.240 --> 00:24:19.605
returned there a year later.

00:24:19.605 --> 00:24:22.200
On his first afternoon
back in town,

00:24:22.200 --> 00:24:25.340
a Tuareg nomad in
his 40s, a gaunt man

00:24:25.340 --> 00:24:28.060
in a ragged turban with
half a dozen children

00:24:28.060 --> 00:24:30.910
playing around him in the
sand, called out to him

00:24:30.910 --> 00:24:33.420
in greeting as he
passed by his tent.

00:24:33.420 --> 00:24:36.000
'Come inside,' he cried.

00:24:36.000 --> 00:24:38.530
Haidara entered the traditional
dwelling stitched together

00:24:38.530 --> 00:24:42.460
from goat skins and sat on the
ground in the semi-darkness.

00:24:42.460 --> 00:24:44.210
He noticed a metal
chest at the rear

00:24:44.210 --> 00:24:47.950
of the tent, the type normally
used to whole manuscripts.

00:24:47.950 --> 00:24:50.260
'You come from where?'
said the Tuareg.

00:24:50.260 --> 00:24:53.760
'I'm from Timbuktu,'
replied Haidara in Tamasheq,

00:24:53.760 --> 00:24:55.480
the language of the Tuaregs.

00:24:55.480 --> 00:24:57.110
In addition to his
native Songhay,

00:24:57.110 --> 00:25:00.290
he was conversant in
Peul and Tamasheq,

00:25:00.290 --> 00:25:02.960
the two other main
languages of Mali's north,

00:25:02.960 --> 00:25:05.690
as well as French, and
thus had no problem

00:25:05.690 --> 00:25:08.860
negotiating with manuscript
owners across the region.

00:25:08.860 --> 00:25:10.200
Haidara made small talk.

00:25:10.200 --> 00:25:12.590
And seeing that the
Tuareg was too poor even

00:25:12.590 --> 00:25:14.370
to offer his visitor
a cup of tea,

00:25:14.370 --> 00:25:16.930
he offered to purchase
some food and drink

00:25:16.930 --> 00:25:18.480
for him and his family.

00:25:18.480 --> 00:25:21.750
Haidara ran out to the
market and returned

00:25:21.750 --> 00:25:24.780
with half of slaughtered lamb
and a kilogram bag of tea.

00:25:24.780 --> 00:25:27.110
The Tuareg grilled the
lamb outside the tent.

00:25:27.110 --> 00:25:30.140
And as they sat eating in the
sand with the man's family,

00:25:30.140 --> 00:25:33.900
Haidara gently broached the
subject of the manuscripts.

00:25:33.900 --> 00:25:36.020
'I don't have any of
those,' the Tuareg said.

00:25:36.020 --> 00:25:38.790
'I only have printed books.'
'Can I take a look?' asked

00:25:38.790 --> 00:25:39.540
Haidara.

00:25:39.540 --> 00:25:42.780
'Why not?' Haidara opened
the trunk and poured through

00:25:42.780 --> 00:25:43.460
the volumes.

00:25:43.460 --> 00:25:45.380
Buried among the
printed material

00:25:45.380 --> 00:25:47.770
was one work that
caught his eye,

00:25:47.770 --> 00:25:49.550
a Koran from the 17th century.

00:25:49.550 --> 00:25:52.560
He looked through it carefully,
noting the delicate Maghrebi

00:25:52.560 --> 00:25:55.110
letters, the fragile gilt
that caught the late afternoon

00:25:55.110 --> 00:25:57.500
light filtering
through the tent flap.

00:25:57.500 --> 00:26:00.980
It was, Haidara
realized, a masterpiece.

00:26:00.980 --> 00:26:03.600
'How much do you want
for this?' asked Haidara.

00:26:03.600 --> 00:26:06.860
'Whatever you want to give
me,' the owner said, shrugging.

00:26:06.860 --> 00:26:12.280
'You have to name your price.'
'Give me 5,000 CFA,' or about

00:26:12.280 --> 00:26:14.180
$10, the nomad said.

00:26:14.180 --> 00:26:16.100
It was a pitifully low sum.

00:26:16.100 --> 00:26:17.620
Haidara could not accept it.

00:26:17.620 --> 00:26:19.870
They bargained, but
this time the buyer

00:26:19.870 --> 00:26:22.231
was bidding up the price.

00:26:22.231 --> 00:26:22.730
'No, no.

00:26:22.730 --> 00:26:25.370
This treasure has a
huge value,' he replied.

00:26:25.370 --> 00:26:30.290
'10,000 CFA.' 'No,'
Haidara said. '20,000.'

00:26:30.290 --> 00:26:33.440
Haidara gave him 100,000 CFA.

00:26:33.440 --> 00:26:35.690
The man received
the money wide-eyed.

00:26:35.690 --> 00:26:38.090
'If I've got more books like,
will you pay for them?' he

00:26:38.090 --> 00:26:39.620
asked. 'Of course.'

00:26:39.620 --> 00:26:42.270
At five o'clock the morning
after that, in total darkness,

00:26:42.270 --> 00:26:44.370
Haidara heard a
knock on his door.

00:26:44.370 --> 00:26:45.390
'Who is that?

00:26:45.390 --> 00:26:46.195
Haidara said.

00:26:46.195 --> 00:26:49.800
The Tuareg entered his room
carrying a large camel skin

00:26:49.800 --> 00:26:50.560
sack.

00:26:50.560 --> 00:26:54.090
Wordlessly, he dumped a pile
of manuscripts on the ground.

00:26:54.090 --> 00:26:57.140
In the murkiness before
dawn, Haidara could barely

00:26:57.140 --> 00:26:58.740
see what was lying there.

00:26:58.740 --> 00:27:01.780
But at six o'clock, golden light
filtered through his window,

00:27:01.780 --> 00:27:04.300
illuminating
magnificent treasure.

00:27:04.300 --> 00:27:06.700
When Haidara stepped outside
the hut later that morning,

00:27:06.700 --> 00:27:08.480
he stared in astonishment.

00:27:08.480 --> 00:27:10.750
Tuaregs from across
the region had

00:27:10.750 --> 00:27:14.420
formed a long line in front
of his door, bearing cattle

00:27:14.420 --> 00:27:17.250
and sheep skin sacks
stuffed with manuscripts.

00:27:17.250 --> 00:27:20.680
Many had been hidden in caves or
holes in the sand for decades.

00:27:20.680 --> 00:27:22.100
Haidara handed
out the equivalent

00:27:22.100 --> 00:27:24.270
of thousands of dollars--
Kuwait and Saudi

00:27:24.270 --> 00:27:26.370
Arabia had subsidized
the effort--

00:27:26.370 --> 00:27:29.020
and left with more
than 1,000 manuscripts.

00:27:29.020 --> 00:27:30.820
He had paid the
seller's everything

00:27:30.820 --> 00:27:32.610
they had demanded an even more.

00:27:32.610 --> 00:27:35.070
He had taken
everything they had.

00:27:35.070 --> 00:27:37.660
Haidara headed back
up river to Timbuktu,

00:27:37.660 --> 00:27:39.850
his boat riding
low in the water,

00:27:39.850 --> 00:27:43.970
weighed down with foot lockers
and piles of camel skin sacks.

00:27:43.970 --> 00:27:48.980
In Timbuktu, Mahmoud
Zouber, the library curator,

00:27:48.980 --> 00:27:50.790
looked on with astonishment.

00:27:50.790 --> 00:27:53.030
'You found all that?' he said.

00:27:53.030 --> 00:27:56.060
In his first year of work
at the Ahmed Baba Institute,

00:27:56.060 --> 00:27:59.150
Haidara managed to acquire
as many manuscripts

00:27:59.150 --> 00:28:01.540
as the previous team
of eight prospectors

00:28:01.540 --> 00:28:04.460
had collected in a decade."

00:28:04.460 --> 00:28:09.220
So I'm going to read one
more section, I think,

00:28:09.220 --> 00:28:14.240
that will give you another look
at Abdel Kader and his methods.

00:28:14.240 --> 00:28:17.670
Basically, after 12
years of doing this,

00:28:17.670 --> 00:28:19.030
he had gotten a bit tired.

00:28:19.030 --> 00:28:22.120
It was grueling work,
obviously-- well paid

00:28:22.120 --> 00:28:24.439
for Malian standards,
but grueling.

00:28:24.439 --> 00:28:25.480
He wanted to get married.

00:28:25.480 --> 00:28:27.940
He wanted to settle down.

00:28:27.940 --> 00:28:29.890
He was spending three
quarters of his life

00:28:29.890 --> 00:28:32.050
on the road in these
incredibly treacherous

00:28:32.050 --> 00:28:34.500
and grueling journeys.

00:28:34.500 --> 00:28:36.059
He wanted to create
his own library,

00:28:36.059 --> 00:28:37.100
as I'd mentioned earlier.

00:28:37.100 --> 00:28:41.190
His family had been collecting
these for centuries.

00:28:41.190 --> 00:28:44.140
So he informed the
curator, who he'd

00:28:44.140 --> 00:28:48.300
become very attached to, that
he wanted to go out on his own.

00:28:48.300 --> 00:28:50.700
They began casting
around for money.

00:28:50.700 --> 00:28:54.340
He needed money,
obviously, to do this.

00:28:54.340 --> 00:28:58.130
Wrote to about 100 different
organizations across the world

00:28:58.130 --> 00:29:03.980
and got absolutely nowhere until
Henry Louis Gates of Harvard

00:29:03.980 --> 00:29:06.050
University came along.

00:29:06.050 --> 00:29:12.410
Now Gates, of course, was one
of America's foremost scholars,

00:29:12.410 --> 00:29:15.210
had spent much of
his life trying

00:29:15.210 --> 00:29:19.670
to show the world-- trying to
move American and the world

00:29:19.670 --> 00:29:21.710
away from a Euro-centric
literary outlook

00:29:21.710 --> 00:29:23.720
and show the Africa
actually had been

00:29:23.720 --> 00:29:27.750
a center of literary tradition
that was completely lost.

00:29:27.750 --> 00:29:33.220
And so he set out in 1996 to
make a documentary with PBS

00:29:33.220 --> 00:29:40.040
and BBC backing about Timbuktu,
about African culture,

00:29:40.040 --> 00:29:46.100
and arrived in Timbuktu in
1996, and began hearing stories

00:29:46.100 --> 00:29:50.930
about this collector
in this town.

00:29:50.930 --> 00:29:57.349
And this is how a fateful
meeting between East and West,

00:29:57.349 --> 00:29:59.390
between Africa and the--
actually, the developing

00:29:59.390 --> 00:30:02.900
world and the developed
world took place.

00:30:02.900 --> 00:30:07.984
So Gates gets to Timbuktu, and
shows up with a certain plan,

00:30:07.984 --> 00:30:09.900
has never heard of
Haidara, has a certain plan

00:30:09.900 --> 00:30:11.996
of going to the mosque
and filming there.

00:30:11.996 --> 00:30:13.370
"But when they
reach their hotel,

00:30:13.370 --> 00:30:15.860
their translator guide, and
acquaintance of Haidara,

00:30:15.860 --> 00:30:18.190
approached them with
a different proposal.

00:30:18.190 --> 00:30:20.270
'If you want to see a
real library,' he said,

00:30:20.270 --> 00:30:22.364
'these books are held
mostly in private hands.

00:30:22.364 --> 00:30:24.780
And there is a man I know who
might be willing to show you

00:30:24.780 --> 00:30:25.900
his collection.'

00:30:25.900 --> 00:30:28.300
Gates, intrigued,
changed his itinerary.

00:30:28.300 --> 00:30:30.440
And he and the film
crew follow his guide

00:30:30.440 --> 00:30:33.330
through the back alleys
to Haidara's house.

00:30:33.330 --> 00:30:36.370
Haidara, meanwhile, was
growing despondent the library

00:30:36.370 --> 00:30:39.390
he had dreamed of creating for
five years was going nowhere.

00:30:39.390 --> 00:30:42.500
More than 100 foundations
had turned down his proposal,

00:30:42.500 --> 00:30:45.070
and he had run out of ideas.

00:30:45.070 --> 00:30:47.874
A big delegation of Americans is
here in Timbuktu,' Gates' guide

00:30:47.874 --> 00:30:49.790
informed Haidara on the
morning of the Harvard

00:30:49.790 --> 00:30:50.927
professor's arrival.

00:30:50.927 --> 00:30:51.760
'They want to visit.

00:30:51.760 --> 00:30:53.343
You they want to see
your manuscripts,

00:30:53.343 --> 00:30:56.140
so be ready.' Haidara sensed
that the visit could be

00:30:56.140 --> 00:30:57.530
an opportunity for him.

00:30:57.530 --> 00:30:58.630
'Fine,' he replied.

00:30:58.630 --> 00:31:01.340
'I'll prepare something
for them.' Haidara lay down

00:31:01.340 --> 00:31:04.280
a carpet and gathered the best
manuscripts in his Timbuktu

00:31:04.280 --> 00:31:05.210
collection.

00:31:05.210 --> 00:31:07.980
Gates and the film crew
arrived later that day.

00:31:07.980 --> 00:31:11.290
As the crew filmed, Gates
leafed through a treatise

00:31:11.290 --> 00:31:14.330
on astronomy, a ledger
book that recorded slave

00:31:14.330 --> 00:31:16.641
transactions, and other works.

00:31:16.641 --> 00:31:18.890
'These are books written by
black people?' Gates asked

00:31:18.890 --> 00:31:21.010
Haidara in a scene
captured on camera.

00:31:21.010 --> 00:31:24.390
Haidara, a bushy haired and
youthful 33-year-old nods.

00:31:24.390 --> 00:31:26.120
'When I was growing
up,' Gates replies,

00:31:26.120 --> 00:31:28.700
shaking his head in amazement,
'the school books said that

00:31:28.700 --> 00:31:31.720
Africans couldn't read and write
and didn't have any books.'

00:31:31.720 --> 00:31:34.760
For hours, Haidara
gave Gates a tutorial

00:31:34.760 --> 00:31:37.400
on Timbuktu's literary
heritage, describing

00:31:37.400 --> 00:31:39.270
the rise of the
University of Sankore

00:31:39.270 --> 00:31:42.380
and its illustrious roster
of biographers, jurists,

00:31:42.380 --> 00:31:46.250
and historians, enumerating
the 12 important families that

00:31:46.250 --> 00:31:48.920
had accumulated most of
Timbuktu's manuscripts

00:31:48.920 --> 00:31:51.440
during its golden age,
chronicling the invasion

00:31:51.440 --> 00:31:54.450
by Morocco that drove most
of these volumes underground,

00:31:54.450 --> 00:31:56.720
and explaining the role
played by descendants

00:31:56.720 --> 00:31:59.220
of Timbuktu's collectors,
who had protected

00:31:59.220 --> 00:32:02.510
the works for 400 years.

00:32:02.510 --> 00:32:05.120
It was one of the most moving
days of my life,' Gates

00:32:05.120 --> 00:32:07.940
recalled. 'I was so
emotional holding these books

00:32:07.940 --> 00:32:11.580
in my hands.' Not a word was
spoken about Haidara's stymied

00:32:11.580 --> 00:32:14.610
plans to build a library,
but Gates left his encounter

00:32:14.610 --> 00:32:17.030
convinced that he had to
do something to preserve

00:32:17.030 --> 00:32:18.090
the manuscript.

00:32:18.090 --> 00:32:20.810
Unprotected and neglected
storage rooms-- many

00:32:20.810 --> 00:32:23.750
we're turning to dust or
being devoured by termites,

00:32:23.750 --> 00:32:25.660
and some had already been lost.

00:32:25.660 --> 00:32:28.710
It was a bone dry climate in
Timbuktu, so he was lucky,

00:32:28.710 --> 00:32:29.560
Gates said.

00:32:29.560 --> 00:32:31.830
If they had been stored in
the humidity of Nigeria,

00:32:31.830 --> 00:32:34.700
they would've turned
to mush long ago.

00:32:34.700 --> 00:32:36.360
When he returned to
the United States,

00:32:36.360 --> 00:32:39.500
Gates informed the project
director at the Andrew W Mellon

00:32:39.500 --> 00:32:42.575
Foundation in New York City
of the amazing discovery

00:32:42.575 --> 00:32:44.600
he had made in Timbuktu.

00:32:44.600 --> 00:32:46.150
All of these books still exist.

00:32:46.150 --> 00:32:47.160
This guy has them.

00:32:47.160 --> 00:32:49.250
And they're not even
in a library,' he said.

00:32:49.250 --> 00:32:50.780
Three months later,
on the strength

00:32:50.780 --> 00:32:53.440
of Gates' recommendation,
the Mellon Foundation

00:32:53.440 --> 00:32:56.880
awarded Haidara grant
of nearly $100,000

00:32:56.880 --> 00:33:00.410
for the creation of a new
manuscript center in Timbuktu.

00:33:00.410 --> 00:33:02.940
The money came with
strings attached.

00:33:02.940 --> 00:33:06.230
Mellon required the collector
to create a digital archive

00:33:06.230 --> 00:33:09.300
before moving ahead with
the physical construction.

00:33:09.300 --> 00:33:10.800
'I know you want
to build a library,

00:33:10.800 --> 00:33:13.490
but the cataloging and
digitization have to come

00:33:13.490 --> 00:33:14.990
first,' Gates emphasized.

00:33:14.990 --> 00:33:17.160
Haidara expressed his gratitude.

00:33:17.160 --> 00:33:19.840
Then he hired an architect
and construction crew

00:33:19.840 --> 00:33:22.790
and built the library anyway.

00:33:22.790 --> 00:33:26.290
'What?' Gates said when Haidara
informed him several months

00:33:26.290 --> 00:33:28.130
later that the
library was complete.

00:33:28.130 --> 00:33:31.280
'I told you that you needed to
catalog first.' 'We can't do

00:33:31.280 --> 00:33:33.844
that without first having a
building,' Haidara replied.

00:33:33.844 --> 00:33:35.260
He argued that the
manuscripts had

00:33:35.260 --> 00:33:37.540
been exposed to the
elements and imperiled

00:33:37.540 --> 00:33:40.770
in their dusty storage rooms
and that his first priority

00:33:40.770 --> 00:33:42.220
was to protect them.

00:33:42.220 --> 00:33:44.590
Exasperated and
fearing a scandal,

00:33:44.590 --> 00:33:47.150
Gates reported the
misuse of the grant money

00:33:47.150 --> 00:33:48.680
to the Mellon Foundation.

00:33:48.680 --> 00:33:51.030
They grumbled about it, but
the attitude, says Gates,

00:33:51.030 --> 00:33:53.870
was, what's done is done.

00:33:53.870 --> 00:33:57.120
A few months later, Haidara
again called Gates at Harvard.

00:33:57.120 --> 00:33:58.960
'What is it?' asked
Gates, still annoyed

00:33:58.960 --> 00:34:00.870
by Haidara's high-handedness.

00:34:00.870 --> 00:34:04.530
'I need another grant to build
another library,' Haidara said.

00:34:04.530 --> 00:34:06.654
'What?' Gates
exclaimed once more.

00:34:06.654 --> 00:34:08.570
'It's amazing that you've
got a grant to begin

00:34:08.570 --> 00:34:11.780
with.' 'I know,' Haidara
said, 'but there was a slight

00:34:11.780 --> 00:34:16.080
miscalculation.' 'What are you
talking about?' 'We built it

00:34:16.080 --> 00:34:17.230
in the floodplain.

00:34:17.230 --> 00:34:18.949
We have to rebuild it.'

00:34:18.949 --> 00:34:21.060
As Haidara explained
it, after many years

00:34:21.060 --> 00:34:23.380
of little or no
rainfall in Timbuktu,

00:34:23.380 --> 00:34:25.760
he and his construction
team had taken for granted

00:34:25.760 --> 00:34:27.550
that the building
site was secure.

00:34:27.550 --> 00:34:29.650
But that year, a
once-in-a-generation series

00:34:29.650 --> 00:34:31.850
of rainstorms had
struck the region.

00:34:31.850 --> 00:34:35.090
Rainwater had deluged the
rooms, cracked the cement,

00:34:35.090 --> 00:34:37.310
and caused the roof to collapse.

00:34:37.310 --> 00:34:40.310
'Everything is filled with
water,' he told Gates.

00:34:40.310 --> 00:34:42.630
Luckily, Haidara
had not yet started

00:34:42.630 --> 00:34:44.960
moving is manuscripts
into the new library.

00:34:44.960 --> 00:34:46.870
And they had all been spared.

00:34:46.870 --> 00:34:50.130
Gates, mortified, went back
to the Mellon Foundation.

00:34:50.130 --> 00:34:53.070
'You remember that library in
Timbuktu that was built without

00:34:53.070 --> 00:34:56.080
your authorization with your
money?' he asked the program

00:34:56.080 --> 00:34:57.220
officer.

00:34:57.220 --> 00:34:58.720
'Yes,' he replied.

00:34:58.720 --> 00:35:01.780
'Well, we've got
to build it again.'

00:35:01.780 --> 00:35:03.830
The program director
just laughed.

00:35:03.830 --> 00:35:07.150
The whole situation was so quote
'absurd' unquote, said Gates,

00:35:07.150 --> 00:35:10.190
and Haidara's demand for
more money so audacious

00:35:10.190 --> 00:35:12.780
that it evoked more
amusement than outrage.

00:35:12.780 --> 00:35:16.230
The Mellon Foundation decided to
come through the extra funding,

00:35:16.230 --> 00:35:19.150
and the Ford Foundation
contributed money as well.

00:35:19.150 --> 00:35:22.170
A new building soon rose
on the site, this one built

00:35:22.170 --> 00:35:25.300
with reinforced concrete and
with its foundation raised

00:35:25.300 --> 00:35:27.010
several feet off the ground.

00:35:27.010 --> 00:35:30.320
On January 13th,
2000, in a ceremony

00:35:30.320 --> 00:35:33.630
attended by many luminaries,
the Mamma Haidara Commemorative

00:35:33.630 --> 00:35:37.910
Library officially opened
its doors to the world."

00:35:37.910 --> 00:35:39.660
Well, that was in 2000.

00:35:39.660 --> 00:35:42.910
And of course, that was
a high point for Haidara.

00:35:42.910 --> 00:35:46.930
And the next few years
would be glory years for him

00:35:46.930 --> 00:35:51.070
as he watched this culture
kind of rise out of the desert

00:35:51.070 --> 00:35:53.800
and begin to attract
more and more money

00:35:53.800 --> 00:35:55.725
and generate more
and more interest.

00:35:55.725 --> 00:35:58.800
And it became sort
of an avalanche.

00:35:58.800 --> 00:36:01.060
Tourists begat more
media interest,

00:36:01.060 --> 00:36:02.550
which begat more money.

00:36:02.550 --> 00:36:05.122
All, of course, came
crashing down in 2012

00:36:05.122 --> 00:36:07.640
with the takeover of Timbuktu.

00:36:07.640 --> 00:36:11.400
And I'm going to save
the smuggling operation

00:36:11.400 --> 00:36:15.380
for your own reading.

00:36:15.380 --> 00:36:17.170
But of course, that
forms basically

00:36:17.170 --> 00:36:23.100
the last 40% of the book as this
elaborate, dangerous operation

00:36:23.100 --> 00:36:27.500
to remove the books under the
noses of the Al Qaeda occupiers

00:36:27.500 --> 00:36:31.660
unfolds with a
still-- well, I would

00:36:31.660 --> 00:36:36.790
stay with a happy, tentatively
happy result, but somewhat

00:36:36.790 --> 00:36:39.230
ambiguous given
everything that's

00:36:39.230 --> 00:36:41.430
going on in that part
of the world right now.

00:36:41.430 --> 00:36:44.210
So at this point,
48 minutes, I'd

00:36:44.210 --> 00:36:49.730
be happy to take some questions
from anybody who's got one.

00:36:49.730 --> 00:36:53.329
AUDIENCE: How long were
you developing that book?

00:36:53.329 --> 00:36:55.620
JOSHUA HAMMER: So I had been
traveling to Mali just out

00:36:55.620 --> 00:36:57.320
of my own interest
over, you know--

00:36:57.320 --> 00:37:02.080
so I visited in '95 on a
lark, as I said, then 2006.

00:37:02.080 --> 00:37:05.225
2008 I went there to do
a whole bunch of stuff.

00:37:05.225 --> 00:37:06.550
I was there for three weeks.

00:37:06.550 --> 00:37:11.090
I did a story on the
festival, on other projects,

00:37:11.090 --> 00:37:12.292
went back to Timbuktu.

00:37:12.292 --> 00:37:13.750
Couldn't find
Haidara at that time.

00:37:13.750 --> 00:37:16.310
He had just-- but I
went and saw his library

00:37:16.310 --> 00:37:18.690
and saw how that had
developed, and then

00:37:18.690 --> 00:37:27.490
came back again in 2013
when the French invaded.

00:37:27.490 --> 00:37:31.330
Because I knew so many people
that when the jihadists took

00:37:31.330 --> 00:37:33.360
over, of course I was
then thinking, well,

00:37:33.360 --> 00:37:35.430
what has happened to those-- I
wondered what would happened.

00:37:35.430 --> 00:37:37.596
It was hard to get any
information out of the North,

00:37:37.596 --> 00:37:38.280
you know?

00:37:38.280 --> 00:37:39.890
So it was just like a vacuum.

00:37:39.890 --> 00:37:42.400
So I guess it was
around that trip in 2013

00:37:42.400 --> 00:37:46.120
then I started to begin
to think about a book.

00:37:46.120 --> 00:37:47.730
But it wasn't
necessarily this book.

00:37:47.730 --> 00:37:51.510
It was just a book about
this dramatic takeover

00:37:51.510 --> 00:37:52.760
of the North in Mali.

00:37:52.760 --> 00:37:56.140
And maybe I would follow some
of the characters I knew,

00:37:56.140 --> 00:37:57.880
the head of the music festival.

00:37:57.880 --> 00:38:01.290
You know, it was all vaguely
formed at that point.

00:38:01.290 --> 00:38:03.527
And then I found out
about the manuscripts,

00:38:03.527 --> 00:38:04.610
what had happened to them.

00:38:04.610 --> 00:38:06.360
I managed to track
down that story.

00:38:06.360 --> 00:38:10.420
And then that became sort of
the most interesting element

00:38:10.420 --> 00:38:11.810
of the any book idea.

00:38:11.810 --> 00:38:16.280
So and I actually then
went back in August, 2013

00:38:16.280 --> 00:38:20.600
to write for Smithsonian
about that rescue effort.

00:38:20.600 --> 00:38:22.770
And by then, that
was when I said,

00:38:22.770 --> 00:38:27.730
yeah, this story, with all the
background, and Haidara's life,

00:38:27.730 --> 00:38:33.100
and the rise of jihadism in
North Africa, I said, you know,

00:38:33.100 --> 00:38:36.040
all these elements have
the makings of a real tale.

00:38:36.040 --> 00:38:37.770
So the book really
began to form then.

00:38:37.770 --> 00:38:40.320
And then two more
trips followed to Mali

00:38:40.320 --> 00:38:44.870
to kind of both piece together
Abdel Kader's biography

00:38:44.870 --> 00:38:48.420
and then to go up to the North
and find out what had happened.

00:38:48.420 --> 00:38:52.710
Because that story was also
pretty much unknown, you know.

00:38:52.710 --> 00:38:55.800
Some people had gone up
with the French-- brief blip

00:38:55.800 --> 00:38:56.874
on the new screen.

00:38:56.874 --> 00:38:59.290
But I wanted to go up there,
and spend like a couple weeks

00:38:59.290 --> 00:39:04.350
there, and meet people, and just
get that whole account of what

00:39:04.350 --> 00:39:08.840
it was like to live under
Islamist Al Qaeda occupation

00:39:08.840 --> 00:39:10.690
for almost a years,
you know, where they

00:39:10.690 --> 00:39:12.390
were building this caliphate.

00:39:12.390 --> 00:39:15.160
Because I thought that was an
important part of the story

00:39:15.160 --> 00:39:18.520
so you could kind
of understand what

00:39:18.520 --> 00:39:22.790
the dangers that the bad-ass
librarians were up against.

00:39:22.790 --> 00:39:26.080
So it needed to be made
as visceral and concrete

00:39:26.080 --> 00:39:27.151
as possible.

00:39:27.151 --> 00:39:28.330
Yeah.

00:39:28.330 --> 00:39:29.580
AUDIENCE: So I had a question.

00:39:29.580 --> 00:39:29.910
JOSHUA HAMMER: Yeah.

00:39:29.910 --> 00:39:31.720
AUDIENCE: So for the
families that are

00:39:31.720 --> 00:39:32.640
preserving these manuscripts--

00:39:32.640 --> 00:39:32.800
JOSHUA HAMMER: Yeah.

00:39:32.800 --> 00:39:33.800
AUDIENCE: --you
mentioned a lot of them

00:39:33.800 --> 00:39:34.847
are in classical Arabic.

00:39:34.847 --> 00:39:35.680
JOSHUA HAMMER: Yeah.

00:39:35.680 --> 00:39:37.265
AUDIENCE: So did
they, you know, know

00:39:37.265 --> 00:39:39.600
the contents of the
manuscripts, or just the fact

00:39:39.600 --> 00:39:40.825
that they were historic,
or what they had?

00:39:40.825 --> 00:39:41.410
JOSHUA HAMMER: Most didn't.

00:39:41.410 --> 00:39:42.870
Most of them didn't
know, actually.

00:39:42.870 --> 00:39:45.119
Because Arabic had been kind
of-- although at one time

00:39:45.119 --> 00:39:47.580
it was the lingua franca
of that part of the world,

00:39:47.580 --> 00:39:49.440
the French conquerors came in.

00:39:49.440 --> 00:39:51.330
Arabic fell by the wayside.

00:39:51.330 --> 00:39:52.890
French became the
language the people

00:39:52.890 --> 00:39:54.810
had to learn in
high schools, those

00:39:54.810 --> 00:39:57.510
who went to school, which
especially up in the North

00:39:57.510 --> 00:39:58.855
is not a great number.

00:39:58.855 --> 00:40:01.890
You know, I think it has one
of the highest-- ironically,

00:40:01.890 --> 00:40:04.860
this region that's produced
some of the greatest

00:40:04.860 --> 00:40:08.530
literature in Africa now has
one of the highest illiteracy

00:40:08.530 --> 00:40:11.660
rates on the continent.

00:40:11.660 --> 00:40:12.550
So yeah.

00:40:12.550 --> 00:40:13.800
I mean, there was scholarship.

00:40:13.800 --> 00:40:14.360
There were people.

00:40:14.360 --> 00:40:15.735
But the people
who learned Arabic

00:40:15.735 --> 00:40:19.220
tended to be those who-- it
was kept inside the family,

00:40:19.220 --> 00:40:19.910
passed down.

00:40:19.910 --> 00:40:22.195
Or they traveled
abroad, maybe learned it

00:40:22.195 --> 00:40:23.154
in Cairo or whatever.

00:40:23.154 --> 00:40:25.070
It was a very small
percentage of who actually

00:40:25.070 --> 00:40:26.880
knew what they had, you know?

00:40:26.880 --> 00:40:28.170
Yeah.

00:40:28.170 --> 00:40:30.100
Yeah?

00:40:30.100 --> 00:40:31.840
AUDIENCE: What's
it like there now?

00:40:31.840 --> 00:40:37.440
Is any of that culture
from the early 21st century

00:40:37.440 --> 00:40:38.595
been resurrected?

00:40:38.595 --> 00:40:40.940
Do the libraries still exist?

00:40:40.940 --> 00:40:43.840
JOSHUA HAMMER: The
libraries exist.

00:40:43.840 --> 00:40:48.484
And the Ahmed Baba Center,
where those-- is still

00:40:48.484 --> 00:40:50.900
a pretty impressive-- I mean,
the South African government

00:40:50.900 --> 00:40:51.460
built that.

00:40:51.460 --> 00:40:54.660
It's like a $8
million structure.

00:40:54.660 --> 00:40:57.870
And I think there are a
couple of curators, you know,

00:40:57.870 --> 00:41:01.040
trying to basically just keep
the building from falling

00:41:01.040 --> 00:41:02.680
completely to pieces.

00:41:02.680 --> 00:41:05.140
But I'm sure that Abdel
Kader's library, which is also

00:41:05.140 --> 00:41:08.290
a really impressive-- more
modest building, but impressive

00:41:08.290 --> 00:41:08.790
still.

00:41:08.790 --> 00:41:12.590
I know he's got a curator
on hand, you know,

00:41:12.590 --> 00:41:15.240
keeping it in shape.

00:41:15.240 --> 00:41:17.690
The manuscripts are in-- the
are no manuscripts in there.

00:41:17.690 --> 00:41:19.820
Well, the Ahmed Baba Center may.

00:41:19.820 --> 00:41:23.530
There were about 10,000 books in
the-- the big Ahmed Baba Center

00:41:23.530 --> 00:41:25.870
was taken over by
the jihadis early

00:41:25.870 --> 00:41:27.820
on and turned into a barracks.

00:41:27.820 --> 00:41:29.952
So that when the
smugglers went to work

00:41:29.952 --> 00:41:31.535
trying to sneak books
out of the city,

00:41:31.535 --> 00:41:32.618
they couldn't go in there.

00:41:32.618 --> 00:41:34.260
Basically, they
figured everything

00:41:34.260 --> 00:41:35.760
in there was going to be lost.

00:41:35.760 --> 00:41:39.310
And in fact, that's where they
torch those 4,000 that I showed

00:41:39.310 --> 00:41:41.080
some pictures of the scraps.

00:41:41.080 --> 00:41:44.540
But 10,000 of them were in
the basement in a climate

00:41:44.540 --> 00:41:47.020
controlled room, locked doors.

00:41:47.020 --> 00:41:49.180
And the jihadis, even
though they lived there

00:41:49.180 --> 00:41:51.480
for eight months, they
never found out about them.

00:41:51.480 --> 00:41:53.970
So those were all preserved.

00:41:53.970 --> 00:41:58.000
But again, like 99% of those
manuscripts are down in Bamako

00:41:58.000 --> 00:41:58.880
now.

00:41:58.880 --> 00:42:01.850
And the libraries are
standing, but they're empty.

00:42:01.850 --> 00:42:05.040
And probably, you know, some
of them are falling apart.

00:42:05.040 --> 00:42:07.860
But the idea is that one day
when things are safe enough

00:42:07.860 --> 00:42:11.345
in Timbuktu, they'll be able
to bring all the books, all

00:42:11.345 --> 00:42:13.610
the manuscripts back
and reopen the libraries

00:42:13.610 --> 00:42:14.360
[SPEAKING ARABIC].

00:42:14.360 --> 00:42:16.365
Who knows when that
day will happen?

00:42:16.365 --> 00:42:17.240
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]

00:42:17.240 --> 00:42:19.323
JOSHUA HAMMER: Well, the
Ahmed Baba Center's books

00:42:19.323 --> 00:42:20.160
have been digitized.

00:42:20.160 --> 00:42:21.320
All those manuscripts have.

00:42:21.320 --> 00:42:24.120
There had been a big program
funded by the South Africans

00:42:24.120 --> 00:42:27.590
not only to restore the actual
works but to digitize them.

00:42:27.590 --> 00:42:29.790
But that Ahmed
Baba Center really

00:42:29.790 --> 00:42:35.500
comprises a small percentage
of this overwhelming 400,000.

00:42:35.500 --> 00:42:38.700
And I think the majority of
those have not been digitized.

00:42:38.700 --> 00:42:40.110
There's a plan intact now.

00:42:40.110 --> 00:42:42.540
They're all kind of
sitting in storage rooms,

00:42:42.540 --> 00:42:43.880
in climate controlled rooms.

00:42:43.880 --> 00:42:48.380
But there's no laboratory-- just
storage facilities, you know?

00:42:48.380 --> 00:42:50.930
And I don't know if
there are laboratories.

00:42:50.930 --> 00:42:54.110
I really don't know what's
going on in that regard.

00:42:54.110 --> 00:42:57.240
Abdel Kader was supposed to
be getting money together.

00:42:57.240 --> 00:43:03.080
I did read it there is this,
interestingly enough, a monk,

00:43:03.080 --> 00:43:06.900
a Minnesota based
monk, who has been--

00:43:06.900 --> 00:43:09.310
and I may even go off and try
to do something about him.

00:43:09.310 --> 00:43:11.680
There's a piece in "The
Economist" about him.

00:43:11.680 --> 00:43:13.750
He's had a long
interest in manuscripts

00:43:13.750 --> 00:43:14.640
from the Middle East.

00:43:14.640 --> 00:43:20.020
He did preserve the masters of
Homs and Aleppo before the war.

00:43:20.020 --> 00:43:22.970
And he has made contact
with Abdel Kader Haidara.

00:43:22.970 --> 00:43:26.900
And I think that has certainly
begun this digitization

00:43:26.900 --> 00:43:27.400
process.

00:43:27.400 --> 00:43:29.460
He's visited Bamako a few times.

00:43:29.460 --> 00:43:32.470
I think I heard that he's
on his way there now.

00:43:32.470 --> 00:43:36.500
So he might be the only
one actually actively doing

00:43:36.500 --> 00:43:37.090
this now.

00:43:37.090 --> 00:43:41.850
But his specialty is in
fact digitization of works.

00:43:41.850 --> 00:43:46.910
He's got into it through
medieval Italian Catholic

00:43:46.910 --> 00:43:50.421
manuscripts and then kind of
gradually expand its interests.

00:43:50.421 --> 00:43:50.920
So yeah.

00:43:50.920 --> 00:43:53.130
I'd be interested to
find out what he's up to.

00:43:53.130 --> 00:43:54.900
MALE SPEAKER: Having said that,
thanks a lot for speaking--

00:43:54.900 --> 00:43:55.280
JOSHUA HAMMER: Thanks.

00:43:55.280 --> 00:43:56.090
MALE SPEAKER: --with
us today and sharing

00:43:56.090 --> 00:43:57.370
the inspirational story.

00:43:57.370 --> 00:43:58.150
Thank you.

00:43:58.150 --> 00:43:59.400
JOSHUA HAMMER: You're welcome.

00:43:59.400 --> 00:44:01.910
[APPLAUSE]

